{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_017AqfYGZebovaz3KtSBNV3r","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see the problem. The `cluster.initial_master_nodes` has all three nodes listed. In ES 7.x, `cluster.initial_master_nodes` is used ONLY for the initial bootstrapping of a brand new cluster. After the cluster is first formed, this setting is ignored and the voting configuration is used instead.\n\nThe voting configuration (stored in the cluster state on disk) still has all three nodes. Since es-cluster-0 only has 1/3 votes, it can't elect itself master.\n\nThe fix is to use `elasticsearch-node unsafe-bootstrap` to force es-cluster-0 to form a new cluster with only itself as the master.\nBut I need to reconsider - when a node restarts, `cluster.initial_master_nodes` only gets re-evaluated if there's no existing cluster state on the PVC. Since the PVC already has cluster state data, the node won't re-bootstrap and will instead try to join the existing cluster configuration. So I need to either delete the cluster state from the PVC or use the unsafe-bootstrap command to force a fresh start.\n\nThe `elasticsearch-node unsafe-bootstrap` command reads the node's metadata and creates a new voting configuration with just that node, allowing it to become master without the other nodes. I'd need to scale down the StatefulSet first since the command requires the Elasticsearch process to not be running, then create a temporary pod that mounts the same PVC to run the bootstrap command, and finally scale the StatefulSet back up. I need to be careful about the PVC mounting constraints—since this is a local-path-storage setup on a single node, the RWO restriction shouldn't prevent the Job from mounting the same PVC after the StatefulSet pod terminates, but I should verify the pod has fully released the volume before the Job tries to use it.\n\nI'm reconsidering whether I can use the `elasticsearch-node` tool while the node is still running, or if there's a live API like the voting config exclusions endpoint that could work without needing to shut down the pod first—though that would require an active master, which I don't have in this broken cluster state. I'm going to scale the StatefulSet to 0, spin up a temporary pod that mounts the same PVC, and run the unsafe-bootstrap command to rebuild the cluster state with just this single node as the voting member. Since the cluster metadata and shard information are stored on disk, the indices should remain accessible once the new cluster forms.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":662,"cache_read_input_tokens":46149,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":662},"output_tokens":27,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0d09739a-17d1-4d89-9637-3d1c569b0d48","uuid":"ea110982-97d4-4012-8b5c-33d67ffd5680","request_id":"req_011CcLPttXN3J7i9E2aLUoGc"}
